WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.334 --> 00:00:02.402
-And obviously,
we have a lot going on, as well,

00:00:02.402 --> 00:00:03.970
because they're balancing
Super Tuesday,

00:00:03.970 --> 00:00:05.705
rightfully so,
with coronavirus.

00:00:05.705 --> 00:00:07.440
-Yes.
-You did a coronavirus piece.

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:08.808
You turned it around
very quickly.

00:00:08.808 --> 00:00:10.710
Personally, there was
more information in that

00:00:10.710 --> 00:00:12.078
than I've been getting
a lot of other places.

00:00:12.078 --> 00:00:14.347
-Okay.
-When did you make the decision

00:00:14.347 --> 00:00:16.849
to do a coronavirus deep dive?

00:00:16.849 --> 00:00:18.384
Because you didn't
have a lot of plans.

00:00:18.384 --> 00:00:20.753
-I guess the answer
to that is, like, it was --

00:00:20.753 --> 00:00:22.922
it was atypical for us,
'cause we decided

00:00:22.922 --> 00:00:24.524
relatively early in our week,

00:00:24.524 --> 00:00:26.592
and we have
something else planned,

00:00:26.592 --> 00:00:29.062
but, occasionally,
there are weeks when,

00:00:29.062 --> 00:00:31.964
if we have something
very timeless and maybe dry,

00:00:31.964 --> 00:00:33.599
that we've been working on,
like, something like --

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:36.068
we've done mobile-home financing
in the past.

00:00:36.068 --> 00:00:38.237
There are certain weeks, like --
I don't know --

00:00:38.237 --> 00:00:41.207
this week where
it's a little harder to say,

00:00:41.207 --> 00:00:44.810
"I know that coronavirus
is spreading across the world

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:47.713
in borderline pandemic fashion,

00:00:47.713 --> 00:00:50.917
but I really need to talk about
mobile-home financing."

00:00:50.917 --> 00:00:52.151
[ Laughter ]

00:00:52.151 --> 00:00:55.221
It's a really hard sell
to be like, "You need to?

00:00:55.221 --> 00:00:56.856
You need to or you want to?"

00:00:56.856 --> 00:00:59.125
in a needlessly
contrarian manner.

00:00:59.125 --> 00:01:02.228
So, yeah.
So, we decided at the start

00:01:02.228 --> 00:01:04.630
of our working week, and so
we crashed it pretty quickly.

00:01:04.630 --> 00:01:05.965
-And how do you feel right now?

00:01:05.965 --> 00:01:08.935
Do you think that we are
suitably panicked?

00:01:08.935 --> 00:01:10.436
Do you think
we're over-panicked?

00:01:10.436 --> 00:01:11.571
-As people?
-Yes.

00:01:11.571 --> 00:01:12.805
-It's on
a person-to-person basis.

00:01:12.805 --> 00:01:14.240
-Yeah, okay.
-It depends.

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.943
On a scale of 1 to 10,
it depends what your

00:01:16.943 --> 00:01:18.944
regular level of panic is
on a good day.

00:01:18.944 --> 00:01:20.146
-Yeah.
[ Laughter ]

00:01:20.146 --> 00:01:21.747
-Me, I'm at
a regular 6 or 7.

00:01:21.747 --> 00:01:24.283
-Yeah.
-So -- So this, you probably

00:01:24.283 --> 00:01:27.587
have to go up a notch
from wherever you were.

00:01:27.587 --> 00:01:29.022
-Gotcha.
-But not too much.

00:01:29.022 --> 00:01:30.556
That's the thing.
You got to try and balance.

00:01:30.556 --> 00:01:32.625
Basically, just don't be
an idiot either way.

00:01:32.625 --> 00:01:33.859
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

00:01:33.859 --> 00:01:37.430
-My wife is a very germ-averse
to begin with.

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:39.265
-In general, right?
Before this happened.

00:01:39.265 --> 00:01:40.733
-Right, whereas I'm not.
-Yeah.

00:01:40.733 --> 00:01:42.201
-So, I think
most of her stress --

00:01:42.201 --> 00:01:44.037
-You love germs.
-I can't get enough of them.

00:01:44.037 --> 00:01:45.171
[ Laughter ]

00:01:45.171 --> 00:01:46.673
-Just looking
for super immunity.

00:01:46.673 --> 00:01:48.842
-Yeah.
-Licking poles on the subway.

00:01:48.842 --> 00:01:49.975
[ Laughter ]
-That's the way I feel.

00:01:49.975 --> 00:01:51.277
-"I'll never die."
[ Laughter ]

00:01:51.277 --> 00:01:53.346
-I feel pretty strong
about that.

00:01:53.346 --> 00:01:55.248
I feel like my --
But that's the thing.

00:01:55.248 --> 00:01:56.950
She's always calling, and she's
like, "Where are you?"

00:01:56.950 --> 00:01:58.684
And I'm like, "I'm at dinner."
She's like, "No, you're not.

00:01:58.684 --> 00:02:00.653
I can see you outside.
You're in the gutters," yeah.

00:02:00.653 --> 00:02:02.021
[ Laughter ]

00:02:02.021 --> 00:02:05.058
-"Are you in Times Square again
inhaling around Elmo?"

00:02:05.058 --> 00:02:07.092
[ Laughter ]

00:02:07.092 --> 00:02:08.761
-So, yeah.
I think her bigger concern is,

00:02:08.761 --> 00:02:10.496
like, what I'm gonna bring home
as opposed to her.

00:02:10.496 --> 00:02:11.897
-Yes, that's fair.
-Yeah.

00:02:11.897 --> 00:02:14.367
-I think that everyone's gonna
have to wrestle with their

00:02:14.367 --> 00:02:17.036
darkest, stupidest instincts.
-Yeah.

00:02:17.036 --> 00:02:19.972
-When my phone went off with
that news alert yesterday

00:02:19.972 --> 00:02:22.708
of someone -- now there's a case
in Manhattan --

00:02:22.708 --> 00:02:25.311
A woman has got coronavirus,
and she's self-isolating.

00:02:25.311 --> 00:02:27.513
There was that initial
split second of,

00:02:27.513 --> 00:02:28.815
"Where is she?"

00:02:28.815 --> 00:02:29.949
[ Laughter ]

00:02:29.949 --> 00:02:32.552
-Yeah.

00:02:32.552 --> 00:02:35.087
-I've never kind of reached
for a flaming torch

00:02:35.087 --> 00:02:37.757
that wasn't there.
And then I shut that down.

00:02:37.757 --> 00:02:39.158
I shut that down
like a human being.

00:02:39.158 --> 00:02:41.427
But there was that split second
of, "Burn her."

00:02:41.427 --> 00:02:45.131
[ Laughter ]

00:02:45.131 --> 00:02:48.034
-I also feel --
I've always felt this way --

00:02:48.034 --> 00:02:49.435
-I hope you're fine.
-Yeah, yeah, of course.

00:02:49.435 --> 00:02:50.569
[ Laughter ]
-I hope you're fine.

00:02:50.569 --> 00:02:51.704
-I think that goes
without saying.

00:02:51.704 --> 00:02:53.272
-I realize,
in self-quarantine.

00:02:53.272 --> 00:02:54.640
-Yeah.
-And we shouldn't burn her.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:56.142
-Yeah.
[ Applause ]

00:02:56.142 --> 00:03:00.446
We actually do --
Our ratings are almost best --

00:03:00.446 --> 00:03:01.747
The demographic
we do the best with

00:03:01.747 --> 00:03:03.215
are people who self-isolating.
-Shut-ins.

00:03:03.215 --> 00:03:05.584
That's right. That's right.
So far, the emotional shut-ins.

00:03:05.584 --> 00:03:08.254
That's why I like this show.
[ Laughter ]

00:03:08.254 --> 00:03:09.455
-I also --
you know that thing where --

00:03:09.455 --> 00:03:12.691
And whenever someone
gives you a stock tip?

00:03:12.691 --> 00:03:14.527
By the time it gets to me,
it's too late.

00:03:14.527 --> 00:03:16.529
-When does anyone
give you a stock tip?

00:03:16.529 --> 00:03:18.097
[ Laughter ]

00:03:18.097 --> 00:03:19.566
Seth,
I know you're a busy guy...

00:03:19.566 --> 00:03:21.200
-I always have lunch
at steakhouses.

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:23.136
[ Laughter ]

00:03:23.136 --> 00:03:24.170
Exclusively.

00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:26.005
I take a full three-hour
steakhouse lunch.

00:03:26.005 --> 00:03:27.573
No, but, like,
even when you see --

00:03:27.573 --> 00:03:29.341
Like, I can't believe
when people watch like CNBC

00:03:29.341 --> 00:03:30.643
or, you know, that --
-Yes, right.

00:03:30.643 --> 00:03:32.145
-If you're watching the news
at a guy saying,

00:03:32.145 --> 00:03:34.247
"Buy this stock," it's too late.
-Yes. That's right.

00:03:34.247 --> 00:03:36.683
-I feel the same way about when
people say, "Stock up on rice."

00:03:36.683 --> 00:03:38.451
-Yes.
-Like, by the time I hear it,

00:03:38.451 --> 00:03:39.918
the rice is gone.
-That's right.

00:03:39.918 --> 00:03:41.387
[ Laughter ]
No question.

00:03:41.387 --> 00:03:42.788
-Yeah.
-No question.

00:03:42.788 --> 00:03:45.691
If ever advice is going out,
you know you're walking into

00:03:45.691 --> 00:03:47.493
the Duane Reade
that has empty shelves.

00:03:47.493 --> 00:03:49.128
-Yeah.
[ Laughter ]

00:03:49.128 --> 00:03:50.963
-Like, if I went now,
I'd come back with, like,

00:03:50.963 --> 00:03:52.532
one orange Gatorade.
-Yeah.

00:03:52.532 --> 00:03:54.033
-It'd be like, "It's all
they had left, honey."

00:03:54.033 --> 00:03:55.468
-Yeah, that's right.
I don't think -- yeah.

00:03:55.468 --> 00:03:58.371
For the stock-market offer,
you know, basic human hygiene,

00:03:58.371 --> 00:04:00.006
I've never moved fast enough.
-Yeah.

00:04:00.006 --> 00:04:01.140
[ Laughter ]

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:03.075
No one has ever given me
a stock tip.

00:04:03.075 --> 00:04:05.411
-You know, I really now --
I shouldn't have told you

00:04:05.411 --> 00:04:07.213
'cause when they give me
the tips, they're like,

00:04:07.213 --> 00:04:09.815
"Obviously, don't tell people."
[ Laughter ]

00:04:09.815 --> 00:04:11.016
"Don't tell
the other talk show hosts

00:04:11.016 --> 00:04:13.586
that we're giving you
these sweet, sweet tips."

00:04:13.586 --> 00:04:16.822
-I just don't know how I'd react
if a stranger came up and said,

00:04:16.822 --> 00:04:18.524
"Do you want a stock tip?"
No!

00:04:18.524 --> 00:04:19.525
[ Laughter ]

00:04:19.525 --> 00:04:20.860
Leave -- no.

00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:23.529
And if a friend told me,
"Would you like a stock tip?"

00:04:23.529 --> 00:04:25.398
I would say, "We're finished."
-Yeah.

00:04:25.398 --> 00:04:26.532
[ Laughter ]

00:04:26.532 --> 00:04:30.336
-A stock tip.
-I give people John tips,

00:04:30.336 --> 00:04:32.538
where I go,
"Don't tell him about stocks."

00:04:32.538 --> 00:04:34.040
-"He doesn't
want to hear about it."

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:36.642
-Obviously, before your show,
you were on "The Daily Show."

00:04:36.642 --> 00:04:38.343
-Yes.
-You were -- You came --

00:04:38.343 --> 00:04:39.712
You famously came from England.

00:04:39.712 --> 00:04:41.781
[ Laughter ]

00:04:41.781 --> 00:04:43.416
You had a show.
-Was this a big give-away?

00:04:43.416 --> 00:04:45.751
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-I'm an American citizen now.

00:04:45.751 --> 00:04:47.119
-No, congratulations.
-Thank you.

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:51.189
-Yeah.
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:04:51.189 --> 00:04:52.592
You were on a show --

00:04:52.592 --> 00:04:54.460
You were on a show
called "Mock the Week."

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:56.428
-I was, yes.
-And this --

00:04:56.428 --> 00:04:57.596
[ Cheers ]

00:04:57.596 --> 00:04:59.332
People know it.
-Right.

00:04:59.332 --> 00:05:01.701
Really?
[ Laughter ]

00:05:01.701 --> 00:05:04.269
-There you go.
It doesn't seem like you get

00:05:04.269 --> 00:05:06.472
a lot of positive feedback
on "Mock the Week."

00:05:06.472 --> 00:05:07.573
-No.
[ Laughter ]

00:05:07.573 --> 00:05:08.875
I don't remember
any at the time.

00:05:08.875 --> 00:05:10.108
[ Laughter ]

00:05:10.108 --> 00:05:12.277
Where the [bleep] were you
a decade and a half ago?

00:05:12.277 --> 00:05:14.480
[ Laughter and applause ]

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:17.383
I was -- I was --

00:05:17.383 --> 00:05:20.820
I was driven to this country by
complete national indifference.

00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:22.021
[ Laughter ]

00:05:22.021 --> 00:05:23.189
-But here's a photo.

00:05:23.189 --> 00:05:25.725
You had a different look
and a different style.

00:05:25.725 --> 00:05:27.560
We found a screen grab
for "Mock the Week."

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:29.195
There you are.
-Yes.

00:05:29.195 --> 00:05:30.997
-That is a different
John Oliver.

00:05:30.997 --> 00:05:33.399
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:05:33.399 --> 00:05:36.168
-Sure.
You can --

00:05:36.168 --> 00:05:39.472
You can turn that sound
into applause eventually

00:05:39.472 --> 00:05:42.741
all you like,
but we all heard the collective,

00:05:42.741 --> 00:05:44.209
"Ohh!"
[ Laughter ]

00:05:44.209 --> 00:05:46.712
We all heard the
instinctive response there.

00:05:46.712 --> 00:05:48.447
-Yeah.
-That is a lot of look.

00:05:48.447 --> 00:05:50.649
-Yeah.
-It feels inconsistent.

00:05:50.649 --> 00:05:53.485
-It is really --
That was a style of shirt

00:05:53.485 --> 00:05:55.288
that was on racks for a very
short period of time.

00:05:55.288 --> 00:05:56.789
[ Laughter ]

00:05:56.789 --> 00:05:59.858
-It's almost like one of those
Olympic sprint cycling helmets.

00:05:59.858 --> 00:06:03.061
There's so much depth to it.
-[ Laughs ]

00:06:03.061 --> 00:06:05.398
-And, yes, I don't know
what material that is.

00:06:05.398 --> 00:06:07.533
It looks like a kind of
leather curtain.

00:06:07.533 --> 00:06:08.767
-Yeah.
[ Laughter ]

00:06:08.767 --> 00:06:10.770
Did you enjoy doing that show?

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:12.605
-Can you --
What does my face suggest?

00:06:12.605 --> 00:06:14.206
[ Laughter ]

00:06:14.206 --> 00:06:15.974
Not my happiest.
-Yeah.

00:06:15.974 --> 00:06:17.309
-Not my happiest time.

00:06:17.309 --> 00:06:20.146
-Well, you've turned it around
in both show and fashion.

00:06:20.146 --> 00:06:23.516
-Oh, what a lovely way to
tie a bow on this conversation.

00:06:23.516 --> 00:06:26.919
[ Laughter ]
Well...

00:06:26.919 --> 00:06:28.187
-There you go.

00:06:28.187 --> 00:06:29.889
No one wraps it up
like this guy.

00:06:29.889 --> 00:06:31.391
John Oliver, everybody.

